</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ucrist0.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Crist0</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(8/3/01 2:44:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=281.topic&index=97>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: humpff</span><hr size=1> Well, as a history buff (I'm not a christian) I've got some little tidbits for you(I don't have specific names/dates right now however I will go get them and tack them on the end of this post later this weekend):<br>
<br>
Something I couldn't let go:<br>
<br>
The statement that the bible has changed a great deal over time to follow politics is completely false. <br>
<br>
In fact, the bible is remarkable in that it is virtually unchanged from its current version to vastly older versions. <br>
<br>
This is proved:<br>
<br>
A) At the ruins of some walled cities in the wilderness around the dead sea area(I believe, like I said i will go get details) inhabited at the time of the Roman invasions by a sect of hebrews who were trying to preserve their religious works(bible) from the invaders. Both their version and the current one are virtually identical.<br>
<br>
B) Dead Sea Scrolls. They support/verify things that are said in the bible.<br>
<br>
C) Other histories written by people in the area/time of the bible's writings (IE Egyptians, Sumerians etc) also support things written of in the bible.<br>
<br>
D Structural evidence from Egyptian digs that supports the Moses era story of no straw for brick building(as well as other non-written evidence)<br>
<br>
As I said, I'm not a religious person, from what I know of it the bible is merely a remarkably unchanged history book.<br>
<br>
It is simply curious that it is so similar to earlier versions(despite what a fewl of you are trying to claim- show me proof, as I can give numerous archeological tidbits to disprove your claim), as a document as old as this one *should* show alot of difference between the newer and older versions.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uefalindrahn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Efalindrahn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Regular Poster</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(8/3/01 4:03:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=281.topic&index=98>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> fun readin'</span><hr size=1> In a broad sense (involving the &quot;universe&quot;)there is no beginning, there is no end. We merely need that idea to cling to, it makes sense to man because we are began in birth and end in death. So we assume that is how it must be with all things. Themes Man made up, only because we are vain enough to believe that the universe functions as we do. As we see life. To think, that these terms, &quot;Beginning&quot;   &quot;End&quot;  all have to do with time, which is another idea we've created to explain what we need so badly to understand. <br>
<br>
&quot;Who was it's father? How old is it? When will it die?&quot;<br>
<br>
How can the world not be flat? The Sun is not a god? Egyptians made runways for aliens? Sasquatch? Loch Ness? The stones of Stonehenge originated where? Rasputin was killed how? Bermuda Triangle? The Holy Grail? Noah's ark was how big again?  Gabriel and Lucifer, a war in heaven? Hell and Hades? <br>
<br>
Yes, religion is just the built in need for us to understand &quot;why?&quot;. It's irritating to not know &quot;why?&quot;<br>
<br>
Religion is based on Dominion. Control. Now...what other force would need to use dominion? Ahh, yes. A governing body uses dominion.  Dominion is something man understands. Kings, Queens, Emperors, Husbands, Wives, Children.......Gods. Is it possible to think any governing body would think to use gods/religion in order to maintain order and control?<br>
<br>
If you really want to be open minded, you will accept that we all must define our existence. The reason is because we reach a point where we become aware of our mortality, and we fear the end of our own time in this world. (Your own belief becomes more powerful when more share your view, it's why some of you are so adamant in pushing your method of thinking to others. An..example of what you hate)We cling to hope, that there's something beyond more pleasant, something greater that we will advance to. The possibility of what it is is horrifying, we each are to an extent frightened because we don't know what's out there. What does man fear most? What he does not know. How does he contend with this fear? By filling in the blank space. Creating a reason for himself and his purpose. <br>
<br>
The politicians, the leaders of societies, knew to make use of this fear. Leaders manipulated the populace with descriptions of what was to come, how it came to be. They discovered they could control the way the masses thought by describing not only a rewarding afterlife, but a consequence for those who did not follow the &quot;right&quot; way. The &quot;right&quot; way, was the method the leaders thought a society should behave. Countless societies have been formed, countless gods, heavens and hells. The most effective means of rule, is to rule by a means that results in fear.   <br>
<br>
Myself, I do believe in the theory that we evolved from the ape (it's understandable for you to scoff, unless you are a scientist who has knowledge of such a process, you're likely offended that a race such as us derived from primitive mammals like them. It seems every bit as believable as an ark with two of every creature, or woman coming from the bone of man. )<br>
<br>
Religion is not a bad thing. I don't say &quot;you blind fool&quot; to the man who follows the teachings of Christ or Allah. I am happy for that man, to discover a positive energy that keeps him smiling day after day. <br>
<br>
That's what is important, after all. To find pleasure, and enjoyment . To grab hold of something positive, and let it keep you until your end comes. Do whatever you must, to control that fear of mortality. <br>
<br>
I have a feeling, that were we to one day answer the question of where we came from, and if there was or was not a god. If we were to discover what happens when we die, and why we were put here.....<br>
<br>
We would not like it, and the result within our cultures would be unpleasant. Sure....some would rejoice...yet<br>
<br>
Imagine the impact of devout believers around the world learning there is no god. Or the other way around. Religion A learns relgion B was right. Hard to stomach. Might make you crazed. &quot;All I've lived for is false ! Release the chemical weapons, Abib !&quot;<br>
<br>
So, while it's fun to speculate the existence of a god. Neither side is sane to believe either side is right or wrong. There's not going to be enough evidence to prove either side wrong or right. So tell it how you think it is, but don't be such a weirdo to believe your way is correct. You just don't know enough, regardless. There's not enough known to have an answer yet. <br>
<br>
I am not a religious man, but I do respect religions. You see,  I respect Order. We have two things that maintian Order. Laws, and religion. The Laws we follow in our societies teach morals that have roots in religion. So, thank god for that. <br>
<br>
I sincerely hope I havn't offended anyone, be there a friend in Norrath I have who is religious or named Abib.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
