<br>
<br>
if you use 110% working with microsoft NET dev why is it still LESS effective and safe then the unix versions from the late 70s?<br>
&quot;<br>
<br>
Lol.... well first of all I'd suggest that you check out the watch lists for server vulnrabilities before you make a statement like that. Also, .NET has nothing to do with being NT, Win2k, Unix, Linux, Solaris, HPUX etc. My 110% remark is simply because the .NET platform is in Beta so there's not alot of documentation out there... no books etc. It's all about figuring it out yourself or asking on the beta mailing lists.  Microsoft personel have been extreamly helpful, however, wich as been a pleasant suprise.<br>
<br>
Second I'd love to compare a unix version from the 70's to a 2000 server today especially when it comes to business applications.  Tho I admit that current unix/linux has almost all the functionallity with less overhead than a Win2k server, the fact is that as a consultant I write for what my clients have.. not what I wish they had.<br>
<br>
Third, the .NET platform is heavly XML based.  What does that mean ? It means the result of my applications, especially the Web Services can be accessed and used by any opperating system out there that supports the ECMA XML standardized format. My server can now talk and exchange information with just about any other server or application out on the internet. My web applications are now compiled in machine code wich means it's faster than a CGI based program and are written now in pure language instead of scripting languages, and I can chose which language I wish to write my program be it C++, C#, VB, Delphi, Cobal etc because as long as it's supported by the .NET framework it doesn't matter which language I use.  I can write an application and easily put a SOAP  wrapper around it, another standardized format.  The .NET platform is a huge leap from the way we, as programmers and developers, do things... a HUGE leap.<br>
<br>
I'd suggest learning a little before taking pot shots at something you know nothing about ;&gt;<br>
